00:05:21.720 --> 00:05:25.090
Now, it won't follow
this structure,

00:05:25.090 --> 00:05:28.150
but if I just move to the next
slide, what I'm going to do

00:05:28.150 --> 00:05:30.670
is actually I'm going to
have convention on the left

00:05:30.670 --> 00:05:34.000
and I'm going to have
possibility on the right.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:36.130
So first, Bombay.

00:05:36.130 --> 00:05:38.200
I know Sooni's sort of
pointed out the fact,

00:05:38.200 --> 00:05:41.740
actually, that Mumbai is
associated with the Shiv Sena

00:05:41.740 --> 00:05:43.696
and it has cultural
connotations.

00:05:43.696 --> 00:05:45.070
I mean, the way
I'm using it, you

00:05:45.070 --> 00:05:49.390
will see is the
possibility that maybe we

00:05:49.390 --> 00:05:51.460
can see a different place.

00:05:51.460 --> 00:05:53.770
And so what I am
suggesting, actually,

00:05:53.770 --> 00:05:59.290
is that Bombay is the island
city that the British saw

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:01.090
and that we still
continue to see

00:06:01.090 --> 00:06:04.840
as an island and a
city that is an island.

00:06:04.840 --> 00:06:07.570
But Mumbai, opening the
possibility that Mumbai

00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:08.740
is an estuary.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:11.470
And what does that do,
actually, to planning

00:06:11.470 --> 00:06:12.910
and the shift in thinking.

00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:14.410
The way in which
we see an estuary--

00:06:14.410 --> 00:06:17.650
I mean, we know of an
estuary as the mouth

00:06:17.650 --> 00:06:23.140
of a river like a delta, except
that the sea comes in as much

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:24.280
as the water goes out.

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:27.970
But in a delta, its more the
river that dominates the sea.

00:06:27.970 --> 00:06:29.620
But what I want
to suggest here is

00:06:29.620 --> 00:06:31.667
that in India during
the monsoons when water

00:06:31.667 --> 00:06:33.250
is everywhere, water
doesn't have time

00:06:33.250 --> 00:06:37.812
to find lines on the map
and so it just flows off

00:06:37.812 --> 00:06:39.770
and so you have an estuary
all along the coast.

00:06:39.770 --> 00:06:42.040
So it's a meeting ground,
actually, of land and sea,

00:06:42.040 --> 00:06:44.800
if you will.

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:48.010
So on the one hand, you see
and plan and you see and plan,

00:06:48.010 --> 00:06:48.730
you draw a line.

00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:51.610
I mean, that's how we got
the coast and the coast

00:06:51.610 --> 00:06:54.550
is actually solidified
into the strong line

00:06:54.550 --> 00:06:58.880
as you can see in this
trajectory of maps.

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:01.030
On the other hand, an
estuary is open to the sea

00:07:01.030 --> 00:07:03.400
and so it calls for
seeing in section.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:04.990
It calls for seeing depth.

00:07:04.990 --> 00:07:07.130
It calls for seeing
actually in time

00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:12.250
so there's a rhythm, actually,
as opposed to this divide.

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:16.510
So on the one hand, we
have marginalized the sea

00:07:16.510 --> 00:07:20.650
by drawing that line and
so you have land and sea.

00:07:20.650 --> 00:07:22.990
But then you've also
marginalized the monsoon

00:07:22.990 --> 00:07:25.030
because then the monsoon
comes as a visitor,

00:07:25.030 --> 00:07:26.920
visits land and goes on.

00:07:26.920 --> 00:07:28.150
That's the way we see it.

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:30.310
So this is a place
where I would like

00:07:30.310 --> 00:07:33.220
to see the monsoon as a
resident, not as a visitor.

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:36.130
So what does it mean,
actually, to shift our mindset

00:07:36.130 --> 00:07:39.040
to an estuary that is
home to the monsoon

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:42.370
and not to the place
for the monsoon

00:07:42.370 --> 00:07:47.440
to be an annual visitor because
in that particular role,

00:07:47.440 --> 00:07:49.300
actually, the
monsoon is becoming

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:52.210
more and more a kind
of enemy and you're

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:53.900
waiting with anxiety
for the monsoon

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:55.410
because it brings flood--

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:57.484
that's what it does.

00:07:57.484 --> 00:07:59.650
Then on the one hand, I
mean the convention actually

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:02.200
could suggest instead of viewing
and plan, you see land use.

00:08:02.200 --> 00:08:05.020
You see land use, you see
land divides and so the island

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:07.180
that you saw there
becomes a smaller island

00:08:07.180 --> 00:08:09.490
and then it divides
into smaller places

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:10.870
and that's how you plan--

00:08:10.870 --> 00:08:13.997
planning is in plan.

00:08:13.997 --> 00:08:15.580
It's not just
foresight, it's actually

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:17.650
comes with a particular
perception and reading

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:21.310
of ground and terrain that
may stem from geography,

00:08:21.310 --> 00:08:24.950
but then, perhaps, geography
is problematic to begin with.

00:08:24.950 --> 00:08:27.580
So what happens, actually,
when you see in section

00:08:27.580 --> 00:08:30.160
and you begin to see
there are practices?

00:08:30.160 --> 00:08:32.800
You don't see land uses,
you see practices in time.

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:35.049
And so when you get the boat
pulled up in the monsoon,

00:08:35.049 --> 00:08:37.539
you get activities
in Bombay that

00:08:37.539 --> 00:08:39.580
operate actually on
the basis of time,

00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:42.169
not on the basis of space.

00:08:42.169 --> 00:08:45.167
And so that's what you
see in an estuary--

00:08:45.167 --> 00:08:46.750
at least I want to
suggest that that's

00:08:46.750 --> 00:08:48.339
what you see in an estuary.

00:08:48.339 --> 00:08:50.380
So what do you have,
actually, are two paradigms.

00:08:50.380 --> 00:08:52.310
On the one hand,
you have a flood

00:08:52.310 --> 00:08:54.790
in drain paradigm where
you're actually draining water

00:08:54.790 --> 00:08:57.190
off the land because
that's the divide that you

00:08:57.190 --> 00:09:00.530
[? had educated ?] into because
you separated water from land,

00:09:00.530 --> 00:09:03.159
flowing, draining,
et cetera, flooding.

00:09:03.159 --> 00:09:03.700
It's a flood.

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:04.720
There's nothing
but water crossing

00:09:04.720 --> 00:09:05.950
a line that were drawn.

00:09:05.950 --> 00:09:08.830
Flood-- if anybody tells you
it's natural, don't believe it.

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:09.470
It's not.

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:12.277
It's water crossing a line
that has been drawn so it's not

00:09:12.277 --> 00:09:14.110
about where you draw
the line, it's the fact

00:09:14.110 --> 00:09:16.300
that you do draw a line.

00:09:16.300 --> 00:09:19.180
On the other hand, you
have a whole soak paradigm

00:09:19.180 --> 00:09:21.850
and an estuary, actually,
where water is held.

00:09:21.850 --> 00:09:25.895
And so when I hold rain,
it's very different way

00:09:25.895 --> 00:09:26.710
of actually seeing.

00:09:26.710 --> 00:09:27.970
I don't see flowing.

00:09:27.970 --> 00:09:29.200
I don't see draining.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:32.560
I don't see rivers,
actually, I just see rain.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:35.560
It requires a certain
dryness to see rivers

00:09:35.560 --> 00:09:36.592
and I want to suggest--

00:09:36.592 --> 00:09:38.800
I think I'm just going to
pass over this because this

00:09:38.800 --> 00:09:43.960
is what happens, actually, in
a project where possibility

00:09:43.960 --> 00:09:46.320
defies convention.

00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:48.790
We look differently,
we see differently,

00:09:48.790 --> 00:09:52.510
and we draw differently and
then we appropriate the ground

00:09:52.510 --> 00:09:53.440
differently--

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:54.970
I won't have time
to actually spend

00:09:54.970 --> 00:09:58.630
on the details of this
project, but you will find it

00:09:58.630 --> 00:10:02.080
in various articles--

00:10:02.080 --> 00:10:04.210
but walking by
anchors, holdings,

00:10:04.210 --> 00:10:07.270
things that live lightly
in a ground in an estuary

00:10:07.270 --> 00:10:12.040
rather than this master
planning that just

00:10:12.040 --> 00:10:14.080
fails again and again.

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:16.270
So if I had to generalize
from this paradigm

00:10:16.270 --> 00:10:21.750
now into what I really
mean, actually, perhaps

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:25.830
more universally, I would
suggest that taking [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:25.830 --> 00:10:29.820
cycle, water cycle, that we
have actually chosen on the left

00:10:29.820 --> 00:10:33.120
by convention to inhabit one
particular moment in time

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:36.630
in the hydrologic cycle when
water can be held in a place

00:10:36.630 --> 00:10:39.070
so it's the realm of flows.

00:10:39.070 --> 00:10:43.050
So I had to look at the water
cycle as going this way--

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:45.670
the flow formation,
evaporation, cloud formation,

00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:48.300
and precipitation--

00:10:48.300 --> 00:10:51.730
we have chosen this moment
to construct a reality

00:10:51.730 --> 00:10:55.020
and we made all the other
moments of water ephemeral.

00:10:55.020 --> 00:10:57.750
And so rain is a
visitor, snow's a visitor

00:10:57.750 --> 00:10:59.100
and they're not residents.

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:01.782
I want to suggest,
actually, that there's

00:11:01.782 --> 00:11:03.990
a possibility of actually
changing the moment in time

00:11:03.990 --> 00:11:06.970
in which we construct reality,
in which we construct nature.

00:11:06.970 --> 00:11:10.050
So if rivers are not
natural, perhaps rain is.

00:11:10.050 --> 00:11:14.250
And then you get a
completely different ground.

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:16.140
So what does it mean,
actually, to design

00:11:16.140 --> 00:11:17.940
with ubiquitous
wetness as opposed

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:19.890
to the land water divide?

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:22.770
And would that suggest a
completely different set

00:11:22.770 --> 00:11:27.690
of disciplines by which we
learn a different understanding

00:11:27.690 --> 00:11:31.680
of the world, really?

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:34.260
So this I suggest for the
ground of the monsoon,

00:11:34.260 --> 00:11:37.520
but I also suggest that it is
a possibility across the world

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:39.270
that we choose a
different moment in which

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:45.990
to construct reality and to
make other moments ephemeral.

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:47.357
How much time do I have?

00:11:47.357 --> 00:11:47.940
Oh, it's here.

00:11:47.940 --> 00:11:49.410
OK, I do have time.

00:11:49.410 --> 00:11:52.290
So on the one hand,
what I'm suggesting is

00:11:52.290 --> 00:11:55.680
that our nature is by choice--

00:11:55.680 --> 00:12:00.030
that nature is not a given.

00:12:00.030 --> 00:12:02.440
This is a subject of
study for the last five,

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:06.680
six years now and it's turned
into a book that suggests that

00:12:06.680 --> 00:12:11.340
rivers are inventions and
that they had been made over

00:12:11.340 --> 00:12:14.940
the years, actually, by literacy
that has separated water from

00:12:14.940 --> 00:12:18.150
land that cannot be
assumed to be natural.

00:12:18.150 --> 00:12:19.340
So what does that mean?

00:12:19.340 --> 00:12:21.040
And you know, it
goes back, actually,

00:12:21.040 --> 00:12:24.060
to the school of Miletus in
the sixth century BC where

00:12:24.060 --> 00:12:26.790
this act of drawing the line
and separating water from land

00:12:26.790 --> 00:12:30.210
was a necessity, actually,
for the Greeks of the school

00:12:30.210 --> 00:12:33.690
of Miletus and they imposed
it in a set of disciplines

00:12:33.690 --> 00:12:34.510
across the world.

00:12:34.510 --> 00:12:36.240
So you know Alfred
North Whitehead

00:12:36.240 --> 00:12:38.460
is famous for saying
that all philosophy is

00:12:38.460 --> 00:12:41.760
a footnote to Plato, but then
if you look at what Plato was

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:44.006
a footnote to,
we'll find that he

00:12:44.006 --> 00:12:45.630
was a footnote to
the school of Miletus

00:12:45.630 --> 00:12:47.160
and their laying
out of an Earth.

00:12:47.160 --> 00:12:50.580
Some so material actually
came before philosophizing,

00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:56.570
if you will, if I can sort of
make a kind of claim there.

00:12:56.570 --> 00:12:59.400
So what I'm suggesting over
here is another moment,

00:12:59.400 --> 00:13:03.230
another time, and
another nature.

00:13:03.230 --> 00:13:07.970
Well, just to give you another
project, in coastal Virginia,

00:13:07.970 --> 00:13:10.860
we're working
there on the coast.

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:13.860
So here I want to suggest,
actually, that on the one hand,

00:13:13.860 --> 00:13:18.430
you have a coastline
where the water's coming

00:13:18.430 --> 00:13:20.820
and we have been in
a community meeting

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:23.420
where people have been
to a drumbeat saying

00:13:23.420 --> 00:13:25.860
water's coming, water's
coming because it is coming.

00:13:25.860 --> 00:13:27.870
In Norfolk, they feel
the seas coming in,

00:13:27.870 --> 00:13:30.960
but that's because we made the
sea an outsider and an enemy.

00:13:30.960 --> 00:13:33.210
So what is this paradigm
that has actually

00:13:33.210 --> 00:13:40.184
constructed that people have
this rising fear of the sea?

00:13:40.184 --> 00:13:41.850
And I want to suggest,
actually, there's

00:13:41.850 --> 00:13:45.180
a whole other way of looking
at this place at Norfolk

00:13:45.180 --> 00:13:48.230
and really looking at the
tide-- you might know what

00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:50.370
is tidewater
country which refers

00:13:50.370 --> 00:13:53.130
to the whole of the
Southern Chesapeake.

00:13:53.130 --> 00:13:56.040
So on the one hand, you have a
coastline that have been drawn

00:13:56.040 --> 00:13:59.250
and it actually was drawn only
when the Europeans actually

00:13:59.250 --> 00:14:00.510
arrived here.

00:14:00.510 --> 00:14:02.520
It was a series
of frontiers that

00:14:02.520 --> 00:14:06.000
came that came across and then
went across the United States,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.266
but there was always a line
that began with the East

00:14:08.266 --> 00:14:09.390
Coast of the United States.

00:14:09.390 --> 00:14:11.910
And the further you went,
the more reinforced this line

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:14.580
became between land and sea.

00:14:14.580 --> 00:14:17.610
And so there are only two
choices then one has over here

00:14:17.610 --> 00:14:21.630
and that is either attack
the sea or defend or retreat,

00:14:21.630 --> 00:14:23.910
I should say, defend
against a sea of retreat.

00:14:23.910 --> 00:14:25.890
So you're talking
with levees, they're

00:14:25.890 --> 00:14:27.780
talking about the
mouth of the Chesapeake

00:14:27.780 --> 00:14:31.710
with gates and all kinds
of ideas like that.

00:14:31.710 --> 00:14:34.590
Oh, and somebody
told me and they say,

00:14:34.590 --> 00:14:36.660
I've got a solution for Norfolk.

00:14:36.660 --> 00:14:39.900
Take all these people and
put them in West Virginia.

00:14:39.900 --> 00:14:43.940
I mean, from that sense
of the retreat following,

00:14:43.940 --> 00:14:46.710
this thing has its own
sort of absurdities.

00:14:46.710 --> 00:14:49.380
But what we suggest
is turn the coast.

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:51.090
Instead of looking
at the line this way,

00:14:51.090 --> 00:14:52.800
look at the line this way.

00:14:52.800 --> 00:14:54.600
Turn the point, I should say.

00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:57.180
Instead of joining
the points like that,

00:14:57.180 --> 00:15:00.530
open the points this way so
that you allow the sea in.

00:15:00.530 --> 00:15:02.250
And then what does that mean?

00:15:02.250 --> 00:15:04.320
I mean you get a completely
different paradigm.

00:15:04.320 --> 00:15:06.921
So here you have barriers
and gates and retreat

00:15:06.921 --> 00:15:08.670
and then you have high
ground, low ground,

00:15:08.670 --> 00:15:11.220
so water doesn't actually
flood, doesn't cross the line.

00:15:11.220 --> 00:15:13.380
Water just rises and
falls and that's the way,

00:15:13.380 --> 00:15:15.640
actually, the Indians
lived in the Mississippi

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:18.720
or the Native Americans lived
in the Mississippi as opposed

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:20.770
to this one where you
actually then have a levee

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:22.017
and you live across the line.

00:15:22.017 --> 00:15:24.100
But this goes into all
deltas and it goes actually

00:15:24.100 --> 00:15:26.380
to the coast, as well.

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:28.770
So you have a paradigm of
fingers of high ground.

00:15:28.770 --> 00:15:31.100
It would be called fingers
of ground and on this side,

00:15:31.100 --> 00:15:33.960
you have levee systems
like New Orleans,

00:15:33.960 --> 00:15:35.980
but you might be a little
more intelligent today

00:15:35.980 --> 00:15:40.210
and actually divide Norfolk into
a number of bowls, if you will.

00:15:40.210 --> 00:15:41.710
So if one floods,
the other doesn't.

00:15:41.710 --> 00:15:44.680
But this is actually
constructing risk.

00:15:44.680 --> 00:15:47.860
And so what is a
system that one wants?

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:50.670
Does one want to define
risk in this manner

00:15:50.670 --> 00:15:54.770
or actually allow for
resilience not to take place

00:15:54.770 --> 00:15:59.425
and, in fact, I missed
that slide earlier on.

00:15:59.425 --> 00:16:02.136
Yeah, here, where they talk
about two kinds of resilience--

00:16:02.136 --> 00:16:03.760
one is a recovery
from disaster and one

00:16:03.760 --> 00:16:06.310
is not getting to disaster
in the first place.

00:16:06.310 --> 00:16:08.650
And it's difficult to
actually argue that,

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:11.110
but it's easy to
design it, if you will.

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:14.890
So what happens here?

00:16:14.890 --> 00:16:18.380
This is just a project that
suggests how this can be done

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:22.396
and we do it in two
places, two sites.

00:16:22.396 --> 00:16:23.770
What does it mean
down the coast?

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:26.800
How does one work with
communities in order to do it?

00:16:26.800 --> 00:16:28.840
How does one do it over--

00:16:28.840 --> 00:16:31.580
like I always say, it's taken us
500 years to get into the soup,

00:16:31.580 --> 00:16:33.760
it will take us another
500 years to get out of it.

00:16:33.760 --> 00:16:36.910
So why don't we start
with that structuring,

00:16:36.910 --> 00:16:40.587
but it requires a completely
different mindset and approach

00:16:40.587 --> 00:16:42.670
that goes down to, actually,
the way we understand

00:16:42.670 --> 00:16:44.840
our disciplines.

00:16:44.840 --> 00:16:48.460
So this just gives
you a sense, actually,

00:16:48.460 --> 00:16:51.940
of how the project develops
and evolves over time

00:16:51.940 --> 00:16:56.290
and how we can sort of
meet the sea in points,

00:16:56.290 --> 00:17:01.600
like that, as opposed to a
line, like that, and accommodate

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:04.072
water treatment
systems with the sea.

00:17:04.072 --> 00:17:05.530
There are many,
many different ways

00:17:05.530 --> 00:17:08.710
by which we allowed
this meeting ground

00:17:08.710 --> 00:17:12.460
to occur in a more open manner.

00:17:12.460 --> 00:17:15.130
So you see, actually,
the existing condition

00:17:15.130 --> 00:17:17.079
here on the left.

00:17:17.079 --> 00:17:19.380
To some extent,
this is recovering

00:17:19.380 --> 00:17:22.161
what we have lost by the
filling of our creeks

00:17:22.161 --> 00:17:23.619
and the destruction
of high ground.

00:17:23.619 --> 00:17:25.869
I mean, Boston is a
classic example, actually,

00:17:25.869 --> 00:17:28.750
of the flattening of terrain
and now we're doing everything

00:17:28.750 --> 00:17:29.720
to regret it now.

00:17:29.720 --> 00:17:32.980
You What do we do to
recover our high grounds

00:17:32.980 --> 00:17:36.340
and to recover creek systems
that were pooling systems,

00:17:36.340 --> 00:17:39.090
not flowing systems-- pooling
systems with fantastic

00:17:39.090 --> 00:17:44.020
ecologies which we
can recover, but it

00:17:44.020 --> 00:17:46.090
means recovering low
ground and you can only

00:17:46.090 --> 00:17:49.630
recover low ground if you start
reconstructing high ground.

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:53.050
So I won't go into how we
are doing it in Norfolk.

00:17:53.050 --> 00:17:57.580
There are many ways
that we can and we've

00:17:57.580 --> 00:18:00.070
established that possibility.

00:18:00.070 --> 00:18:02.320
I think I've reached
the end of my show here.

00:18:02.320 --> 00:18:08.205
And this is I dared to take on
Einstein a little bit here so I

00:18:08.205 --> 00:18:10.330
say that we cannot solve
our problems with the same

00:18:10.330 --> 00:18:10.930
thinking.

00:18:10.930 --> 00:18:12.346
I mean, he said
the same thinking,

00:18:12.346 --> 00:18:15.400
I'm saying you cannot solve the
problems with the same nature

00:18:15.400 --> 00:18:18.460
that went into creating them.

00:18:18.460 --> 00:18:20.760
So what I'm
suggesting is that we

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:23.740
got to start thinking of
another place, another time.

00:18:23.740 --> 00:18:24.588
Thank you.

00:18:24.588 --> 00:18:27.028
[APPLAUSE]

00:18:35.330 --> 00:18:39.110
- It is such an
honor to be back.

00:18:39.110 --> 00:18:41.690
I love this place
and its people and I

00:18:41.690 --> 00:18:44.930
thank the staff so very
much for having organized

00:18:44.930 --> 00:18:48.350
this conference with these
incredibly inspiring colleagues

00:18:48.350 --> 00:18:49.340
of mine.

00:18:49.340 --> 00:18:51.530
Thank you for being here.

00:18:51.530 --> 00:18:57.740
I am going to give you a
glimpse of my creative process.

00:18:57.740 --> 00:19:01.370
Some of the projects that touch
on urbanism, specifically,

00:19:01.370 --> 00:19:07.140
and some that, perhaps, hope
to expand the concept of it.

00:19:07.140 --> 00:19:09.435
My work often
begins with a site,

00:19:09.435 --> 00:19:15.340
a setting that needs to be
explored, that can be wandered,

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:18.240
of which I then
become the wanderer.

00:19:18.240 --> 00:19:21.300
They're public and
not so public sites.

00:19:21.300 --> 00:19:24.450
I'm drawn to the
more hidden corners

00:19:24.450 --> 00:19:27.810
of public life, the blurred
edges of our communities,

00:19:27.810 --> 00:19:30.120
large and small.

00:19:30.120 --> 00:19:33.160
At the Rhode Island School
of Design, I studied painting

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:35.270
and if you held
a gun to my head,

00:19:35.270 --> 00:19:36.520
I would say that's what I am--

00:19:36.520 --> 00:19:37.920
I am a painter--

00:19:37.920 --> 00:19:42.120
but everything that I've
done since studying painting

00:19:42.120 --> 00:19:45.360
and graduating as a
painter has sort of

00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:50.700
explored the edges of
painting and wandered off

00:19:50.700 --> 00:19:53.790
into larger media.

00:19:53.790 --> 00:19:57.000
I had to accept painting
as a two dimensional medium

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:01.830
and wondered how that medium
would relate to the surrounding

00:20:01.830 --> 00:20:05.280
world, it's outside sources.

00:20:05.280 --> 00:20:08.370
So I came to my work as a
pedestrian with the wish

00:20:08.370 --> 00:20:10.770
to somehow capture the
enormous architecture

00:20:10.770 --> 00:20:14.820
I was interested in at that
time as a young student,

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:17.910
specifically
psychiatric hospitals,

00:20:17.910 --> 00:20:20.430
through drawings and paintings.

00:20:20.430 --> 00:20:23.880
From across the
overgrown lawn, I

00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:28.140
recorded my walks using
them as my hand-drawn record

00:20:28.140 --> 00:20:30.990
of my interaction with the site.

00:20:30.990 --> 00:20:33.620
Based on my interest in
map reading and mapmaking,

00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:39.450
they became a form of
remembered orientation in space.

00:20:39.450 --> 00:20:44.670
And my first works were
a failing of painting

00:20:44.670 --> 00:20:48.030
and that I realized
there's really no reason

00:20:48.030 --> 00:20:51.920
to paint these buildings but to
collect what's already there,

00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:53.700
to gather what's already there.

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:58.410
And passing through each
room in these institutions,

00:20:58.410 --> 00:21:00.420
I would take a paint sample--

00:21:00.420 --> 00:21:03.330
it was all lead paint.

00:21:03.330 --> 00:21:08.370
So this is my walk through
the building in linear terms

00:21:08.370 --> 00:21:10.620
from left to right.

00:21:10.620 --> 00:21:14.790
And the larger boxes
are larger spaces,

00:21:14.790 --> 00:21:18.490
the smaller ones, the square
ones, are patient cells.

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:26.270
In its widest sense, I'm
curious about the imprint

00:21:26.270 --> 00:21:30.290
that the urban environment has
on us as its users, citizens,

00:21:30.290 --> 00:21:33.230
and the members of
the communities--

00:21:33.230 --> 00:21:37.080
how we navigate our environment,
how we make sense of it,

00:21:37.080 --> 00:21:39.080
how we derive meaning
from it, and how

00:21:39.080 --> 00:21:43.250
we give back meaning to it.

00:21:43.250 --> 00:21:51.220
I found this place in outside
Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.

00:21:51.220 --> 00:21:54.180
This is the Dixmont
State Hospital--

00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:56.970
the center of it, before
it was torn down--

00:21:56.970 --> 00:21:59.520
and the oculus
that you see there

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:04.080
has, as Dorothea Dix, the
reformer of the 19th century

00:22:04.080 --> 00:22:07.320
said, one of the most beautiful
views of North America.

00:22:12.260 --> 00:22:14.570
The French philosopher
Gaston Bachelard

00:22:14.570 --> 00:22:17.210
described the
motionless daydreamer

00:22:17.210 --> 00:22:20.330
as experiencing an
immensity of being.

00:22:20.330 --> 00:22:23.540
He said immensity
is within ourselves.

00:22:23.540 --> 00:22:27.080
It is attached to a sort of
expansion of being that life

00:22:27.080 --> 00:22:30.230
curbs and caution arrests,
but which starts again

00:22:30.230 --> 00:22:31.640
when we were alone.

00:22:31.640 --> 00:22:36.500
As soon as we become motionless,
we are dreaming in a world that

00:22:36.500 --> 00:22:37.790
is a man's.

00:22:37.790 --> 00:22:44.320
Indeed, immensity is the
movement of motionless man.

00:22:44.320 --> 00:22:49.900
So my first project, one
that is I think breaking away

00:22:49.900 --> 00:22:53.470
from urbanism, was
a daydream to me

00:22:53.470 --> 00:22:59.230
and it was cited here at this
hospital, Northampton State

00:22:59.230 --> 00:23:03.340
Hospital, with its
vast interiors,

00:23:03.340 --> 00:23:08.600
hallways that would allow
a car to pass through.

00:23:08.600 --> 00:23:11.350
It was a large scale
science specific sound voice

00:23:11.350 --> 00:23:13.120
performance at
Northampton State Hospital

00:23:13.120 --> 00:23:17.560
spanning 414,000 square feet
of connected space using

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:22.560
the hallways and rooms of
the abandoned structure.

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:25.070
Like the insides of an
instrument, a sound body,

00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:26.680
this was my first
project that took me

00:23:26.680 --> 00:23:28.420
beyond the parameters
of painting

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:33.460
clearly and placed me in a more
experimental and performative

00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:36.360
realm.

00:23:36.360 --> 00:23:38.820
It was a form of
architectural dreaming

00:23:38.820 --> 00:23:42.960
without touching the building
at all because sound lives in it

00:23:42.960 --> 00:23:45.480
and then disappears again.

00:23:45.480 --> 00:23:47.580
I was able to work with
the entire building

00:23:47.580 --> 00:23:52.170
without moving an inch
of it or any of it.

00:23:52.170 --> 00:23:54.540
I realized the painting
was not large enough,

00:23:54.540 --> 00:23:56.920
not inclusive enough.

00:23:56.920 --> 00:23:59.650
Sound was the only
medium for me.

00:23:59.650 --> 00:24:01.990
I thought I could animate
the entire architecture

00:24:01.990 --> 00:24:05.110
without disturbing it,
interrupting it, reshaping

00:24:05.110 --> 00:24:06.140
it, or reducing it.

00:24:09.260 --> 00:24:14.690
So this was the set up we strung
thousands of feet of cable

00:24:14.690 --> 00:24:18.860
through the building and
connected the entire hospital

00:24:18.860 --> 00:24:21.250
with itself.

00:24:21.250 --> 00:24:26.140
And this is the back wards.

00:24:26.140 --> 00:24:31.410
This is where patients
used to be who were violent

00:24:31.410 --> 00:24:34.710
and often there
for decades on end.

00:24:34.710 --> 00:24:38.790
And the sound was meant to be
bounced through the building

00:24:38.790 --> 00:24:41.040
by bouncing it off
a surface first.

00:24:41.040 --> 00:24:43.020
We didn't let it get
out of the windows

00:24:43.020 --> 00:24:45.660
right away, but rather
using the building

00:24:45.660 --> 00:24:52.170
to take on its
color, it's solidity,

00:24:52.170 --> 00:24:53.670
and changing the sound thereby.

00:24:56.570 --> 00:25:01.320
The sound I chose was Johann
Sebastian Bach's Magnificat

00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:04.620
because I had been a
choir girl and because I

00:25:04.620 --> 00:25:08.400
love that piece of music
and because I remembered it

00:25:08.400 --> 00:25:11.390
every time I was
in this building--

00:25:11.390 --> 00:25:15.500
like a physical memory,
it came back to me.

00:25:15.500 --> 00:25:17.750
So this is the
solarium it was called

00:25:17.750 --> 00:25:24.760
in one of the easier units where
patients had small freedoms.

00:25:24.760 --> 00:25:27.370
And then we invited
an unknown public

00:25:27.370 --> 00:25:29.560
to come and listen to this.

00:25:29.560 --> 00:25:32.050
The entire thing
was only 28 minutes.

00:25:32.050 --> 00:25:35.050
It took four years
to do and we didn't

00:25:35.050 --> 00:25:37.810
know who was going to come,
but the state hospital

00:25:37.810 --> 00:25:41.320
was long closed and there was
no trespassing, of course,

00:25:41.320 --> 00:25:46.060
and we broke the rules for that
one day for that one half hour

00:25:46.060 --> 00:25:47.260
and thousands showed up.

00:25:47.260 --> 00:25:51.530
This was in Northampton,
Massachusetts.

00:25:51.530 --> 00:25:54.140
And I didn't let people
into the building

00:25:54.140 --> 00:25:56.620
for, obviously,
liability reasons,

00:25:56.620 --> 00:25:59.360
but I also didn't want
them to play haunted house.

00:25:59.360 --> 00:26:02.120
I wanted them to give
the building its presence

00:26:02.120 --> 00:26:05.470
and allow the building to sound.

00:26:05.470 --> 00:26:07.690
And this is how some of
the people experienced it.

00:26:12.540 --> 00:26:17.130
I went back to painting so
back to recording my walks

00:26:17.130 --> 00:26:23.070
and I didn't know
how after doing

00:26:23.070 --> 00:26:27.120
that, after connecting with an
entire community of volunteers,

00:26:27.120 --> 00:26:32.760
sound engineers, politicians,
lobbyists, students,

00:26:32.760 --> 00:26:35.520
I would then go back to
being a single painter.

00:26:35.520 --> 00:26:38.820
And I decided that that's
just all I wanted to do,

00:26:38.820 --> 00:26:42.270
but the next project was
a project which I'm just

00:26:42.270 --> 00:26:44.850
going to show two slides of.

00:26:44.850 --> 00:26:48.210
It was for the Massachusetts
Mental Health Center

00:26:48.210 --> 00:26:49.860
here in Boston.

00:26:49.860 --> 00:26:52.770
The same sort of building,
but very different.

00:26:52.770 --> 00:26:59.280
50 years later, it closed
and Harvard Medical School

00:26:59.280 --> 00:27:02.730
Department of Psychiatry
asked me to do the music again

00:27:02.730 --> 00:27:04.800
and I decided I wasn't
going to do that--

00:27:04.800 --> 00:27:06.870
that was site
specific, but I was

00:27:06.870 --> 00:27:10.140
going to work with a building
in a different way and by then,

00:27:10.140 --> 00:27:16.680
I had experienced hospitals
as a visiting artist

00:27:16.680 --> 00:27:19.980
and I realized that patients
were not receiving any flowers.

00:27:19.980 --> 00:27:25.440
So we gathered-- we, my
team of 80 and myself--

00:27:25.440 --> 00:27:30.610
gathered 28,000
flowers and spread them

00:27:30.610 --> 00:27:33.820
throughout the building in
a gesture of giving back

00:27:33.820 --> 00:27:35.320
to the building
that which had been

00:27:35.320 --> 00:27:40.030
missing since patients
in psychiatry rarely

00:27:40.030 --> 00:27:43.140
receive flowers.

00:27:43.140 --> 00:27:47.940
The project existed for four
days, not 28 minutes, four days

00:27:47.940 --> 00:27:52.410
and afterwards, we returned all
the flowers which were potted--

00:27:52.410 --> 00:27:53.560
none of them were cut--

00:27:53.560 --> 00:27:54.760
to people behind bars.

00:27:59.580 --> 00:28:02.420
So what I learned in public
art projects was became

00:28:02.420 --> 00:28:05.030
crucial what then
happened which was

00:28:05.030 --> 00:28:08.600
I wanted to connect with sites
and settings on a large scale,

00:28:08.600 --> 00:28:11.630
but I didn't want to make
public art, I wanted to paint.

00:28:11.630 --> 00:28:13.040
The next project
was a commission

00:28:13.040 --> 00:28:17.750
for a very ugly concrete
wall in Western Massachusetts

00:28:17.750 --> 00:28:20.720
on the campus of UMass Amherst.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.780
And I proposed to
paint a large painting

00:28:23.780 --> 00:28:25.670
and they were very disappointed.

00:28:25.670 --> 00:28:27.800
They wanted something
spectacularly

00:28:27.800 --> 00:28:29.780
strange and
interdisciplinary and I

00:28:29.780 --> 00:28:33.110
said it's just going
to be a painting.

00:28:33.110 --> 00:28:35.780
But the painting I
conceived of was the face

00:28:35.780 --> 00:28:37.550
of an agricultural worker--

00:28:37.550 --> 00:28:39.944
it used to be an
agricultural school--

00:28:39.944 --> 00:28:42.110
that I found in the archives
doing my research there

00:28:42.110 --> 00:28:46.220
and all I wanted to
do was to paint it

00:28:46.220 --> 00:28:52.910
upside down so that you would
only see it in the water.

00:28:52.910 --> 00:28:55.400
I did not tell anyone
how to use this work,

00:28:55.400 --> 00:28:58.250
but wanted students
to discover it.

00:28:58.250 --> 00:29:02.120
So it was called Just a
Rumor and the ducks that

00:29:02.120 --> 00:29:06.800
live on this pond became my
collaborators because they

00:29:06.800 --> 00:29:08.951
would wipe out the entire
painting by swimming

00:29:08.951 --> 00:29:09.950
through it all the time.

00:29:13.800 --> 00:29:18.090
There's one photo and this is it
that shows, oh, you can see it,

00:29:18.090 --> 00:29:21.380
but it's a little dark, but
there are four ducks parked

00:29:21.380 --> 00:29:23.960
in the face without swimming,
they're not pedaling,

00:29:23.960 --> 00:29:26.220
and therefore you can see it.

00:29:26.220 --> 00:29:29.330
They're just asleep
on the surface.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:32.810
And then it froze and
we all forgot about it

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:34.999
and when spring came, it
thawed and we remembered

00:29:34.999 --> 00:29:36.290
that the piece was still there.

00:29:39.440 --> 00:29:42.130
And based on that, I
went back to my studio

00:29:42.130 --> 00:29:45.970
again as a painter, as someone
who loves to draw and paint

00:29:45.970 --> 00:29:52.240
with my pens and brushes,
and I felt what if I create

00:29:52.240 --> 00:29:57.340
works that work with that
scale, but are using my most

00:29:57.340 --> 00:30:00.910
beloved medium in another way.

00:30:00.910 --> 00:30:03.460
And I was offered by
neuroscientists at Columbia

00:30:03.460 --> 00:30:07.150
Medical School to collaborate
with them on a project that

00:30:07.150 --> 00:30:10.930
uses eye tracking technology
that is attached to your pupil

00:30:10.930 --> 00:30:12.940
so you don't use your
hands at all to draw,

00:30:12.940 --> 00:30:14.912
but you use your eyes only.

00:30:14.912 --> 00:30:16.870
And this is a drawing,
this is my first drawing

00:30:16.870 --> 00:30:19.440
ever with my pupil only.

00:30:19.440 --> 00:30:22.540
A camera records
where I'm looking

00:30:22.540 --> 00:30:26.660
and each glance, every
direction my eyes make,

00:30:26.660 --> 00:30:29.650
is recorded so I have to
be very careful and slow.

00:30:29.650 --> 00:30:33.370
And this is a bicycle on the
right side going down hill--

00:30:33.370 --> 00:30:36.130
you can maybe tell.

00:30:36.130 --> 00:30:40.030
And based on that,
I decided what

00:30:40.030 --> 00:30:46.450
if I create live drawings that
are truly touching the surfaces

00:30:46.450 --> 00:30:48.220
I'm interested in,
those buildings

00:30:48.220 --> 00:30:53.590
and sites and settings, for
example, a stage with dancers.

00:30:53.590 --> 00:30:56.500
I was offered a
collaboration with dancers.

00:30:56.500 --> 00:31:00.460
This is a draft for it and
then this was the actual dance.

00:31:00.460 --> 00:31:03.610
The person, the dancer,
had taken a break

00:31:03.610 --> 00:31:06.700
after a solo, laid
down, and I was

00:31:06.700 --> 00:31:09.880
able to draw her
a blanket of lines

00:31:09.880 --> 00:31:12.340
by using very high
tech projectors in New

00:31:12.340 --> 00:31:17.750
York on a beautiful stage and it
was a live drawing performance.

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:19.450
So that's what I'm doing now.

00:31:19.450 --> 00:31:22.690
I'm creating these drawings
that happen in actual time.

00:31:22.690 --> 00:31:25.600
They're not canned,
they're not video.

00:31:25.600 --> 00:31:31.950
This is an eye
tracking drawing that I

00:31:31.950 --> 00:31:34.800
conceived for that Cooper
Hewitt Museum in New York.

00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:35.880
This is the facade of it.

00:31:35.880 --> 00:31:38.910
It was not realized
because of budget reasons,

00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:44.580
but it was a drawing I did with
my eyes looking at a Man Ray

00:31:44.580 --> 00:31:47.130
photograph that you all
know, with the eyelashes

00:31:47.130 --> 00:31:47.850
and the tear.

00:31:50.670 --> 00:31:53.070
And the straight
lines that come off it

00:31:53.070 --> 00:31:56.520
are lines that are
made by my blinking.

00:32:01.020 --> 00:32:03.450
And most recently,
these are smaller scale,

00:32:03.450 --> 00:32:07.710
but still wall sized
live drawings transmitted

00:32:07.710 --> 00:32:11.820
from New Orleans to Hanover,
New Hampshire for the Dartmouth

00:32:11.820 --> 00:32:13.830
Biannual.

00:32:13.830 --> 00:32:16.230
Every morning, I
made a drawing that

00:32:16.230 --> 00:32:22.980
was wired over to Dartmouth and
it was projected onto this wall

00:32:22.980 --> 00:32:24.660
very slowly.

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:29.700
So these are drawings created
for that wall in my absence

00:32:29.700 --> 00:32:34.520
by me in a different state.

00:32:34.520 --> 00:32:37.790
And we did 90 of these indoor
drawings-- one every day--

00:32:37.790 --> 00:32:42.680
and then 12 for the outdoor
courtyard of the Hood Museum.

00:32:42.680 --> 00:32:51.960
So here is one of them and
here is another and another.

00:32:51.960 --> 00:32:54.180
This is a goat, of course.

00:32:54.180 --> 00:32:58.380
And this is my
last slide for now,

00:32:58.380 --> 00:33:06.130
a drawing of a hand created
live so it is moving.

00:33:06.130 --> 00:33:08.850
So this is just a still of
that touching the surface

00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:10.130
of the Hood Museum's back.

00:33:14.990 --> 00:33:17.060
I am so grateful
to have been here.

00:33:17.060 --> 00:33:18.317
Thank you so much.

00:33:18.317 --> 00:33:20.702
[APPLAUSE]

00:33:26.999 --> 00:33:28.540
- Good afternoon
and thanks, as well,

00:33:28.540 --> 00:33:31.600
for the invitation by
the Radcliffe Institute.

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:36.700
We are very honored to be here
and we will talk about nature,

00:33:36.700 --> 00:33:40.730
technology, and culture.

00:33:40.730 --> 00:33:41.270
- OK.

00:33:41.270 --> 00:33:46.240
Our panel is called "Beyond the
Nature and Technology Divide."

00:33:46.240 --> 00:33:50.120
And my first thought as an
architect hearing this title

00:33:50.120 --> 00:33:54.540
was, if there is a dividing line
between nature and technology,

00:33:54.540 --> 00:33:57.215
jumping over it is the
typical behavior for people

00:33:57.215 --> 00:34:02.810
who have the profession of my
husband or climate engineers.

00:34:02.810 --> 00:34:06.430
Because in their everyday
work, climate engineers

00:34:06.430 --> 00:34:11.630
are measuring and
evaluating and interpreting

00:34:11.630 --> 00:34:15.400
physical that is natural--

00:34:15.400 --> 00:34:18.290
parametrics about
temperature, about light,

00:34:18.290 --> 00:34:23.540
material, concluding technical
concepts out of them.

00:34:23.540 --> 00:34:28.010
As soon as these concepts become
part of architecture or, even

00:34:28.010 --> 00:34:32.600
more complex, part of urban
planning and these projects

00:34:32.600 --> 00:34:37.360
get realized by
interdisciplinary teams,

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:40.940
culture pops up
as the term which

00:34:40.940 --> 00:34:44.690
besides nature and technology.

00:34:44.690 --> 00:34:48.770
These three terms became
the title of our talk

00:34:48.770 --> 00:34:52.050
and the basis for our
thoughts and research.

00:34:56.440 --> 00:35:00.680
To get familiar with the
urbanism in the global age,

00:35:00.680 --> 00:35:05.150
we were tracing back
the history of settling

00:35:05.150 --> 00:35:10.070
from today's megacities to
the very beginning of humanity

00:35:10.070 --> 00:35:12.860
and human settlements.

00:35:12.860 --> 00:35:17.450
We observed a specific
interdependence

00:35:17.450 --> 00:35:19.910
of these three factors--

00:35:19.910 --> 00:35:24.860
nature, technology,
and culture--

00:35:24.860 --> 00:35:29.060
in every period of
settling and each factor

00:35:29.060 --> 00:35:33.970
with different impact or
importance [? in ?] the period.

00:35:33.970 --> 00:35:36.940
I don't know if
it's early for that.

00:35:36.940 --> 00:35:42.020
Related to six billion
years of Earth's history

00:35:42.020 --> 00:35:45.880
at a time 2.8 million years
since the genesis of humanity

00:35:45.880 --> 00:35:48.460
is nearly nothing.

00:35:53.470 --> 00:35:57.960
In the Pleistocene, 2.6 million
to 10,000 years before Christ,

00:35:57.960 --> 00:36:01.520
is the first and very long
period of human settlement

00:36:01.520 --> 00:36:04.950
and it's characterized
by a specific climate,

00:36:04.950 --> 00:36:10.650
by the change between ice
ages and warmer periods.

00:36:10.650 --> 00:36:12.930
At that time,
settlement was totally

00:36:12.930 --> 00:36:17.940
based on nature and
natural conditions.

00:36:17.940 --> 00:36:21.510
This cave is called Hohle Fels.

00:36:21.510 --> 00:36:23.640
It's in southern Germany.

00:36:23.640 --> 00:36:31.060
It was inhabited for a very long
time and remains of mammoths,

00:36:31.060 --> 00:36:38.350
spears, and white horses were
found and the very first known

00:36:38.350 --> 00:36:45.220
piece of art, this Venus, which
is about 35,000 years old.

00:36:45.220 --> 00:36:49.060
It's like this,
carved from ivory

00:36:49.060 --> 00:36:51.910
and a great cultural
contribution.

00:36:56.630 --> 00:37:00.200
After the last ice age,
climate stayed nearly constant

00:37:00.200 --> 00:37:05.510
from 10,000 before Christ to
let's say 1800 after Christ.

00:37:05.510 --> 00:37:10.920
This period is called Holocene
and the climate conditions

00:37:10.920 --> 00:37:16.545
were very good for a
widespread cultural blooming.

00:37:19.290 --> 00:37:21.810
Nearly everything
we call culture

00:37:21.810 --> 00:37:25.320
was developed in this period--

00:37:25.320 --> 00:37:33.220
writing, architecture, a lot
of new science, knowledge.

00:37:36.760 --> 00:37:43.010
It's no accident that all
the high culture developed

00:37:43.010 --> 00:37:46.640
in this period in Egypt, all
over the world-- in China,

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:48.640
in the Middle East, and so on.

00:37:51.460 --> 00:37:55.090
This diagram shows the
Holocene temperature profile

00:37:55.090 --> 00:37:56.800
I already mentioned.

00:37:56.800 --> 00:38:00.200
After the long
period with ice ages,

00:38:00.200 --> 00:38:06.010
you can see that in the
Holocene, about 10,000 years,

00:38:06.010 --> 00:38:10.450
temperature only decreases
for half a degree.

00:38:10.450 --> 00:38:14.800
And nowadays, we expect a
man-made temperature change

00:38:14.800 --> 00:38:20.185
increase between 1.5 and
3 degrees within 50 years.

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:26.530
This picture of our
illuminated planet

00:38:26.530 --> 00:38:29.170
represents the period
we are living in now.

00:38:29.170 --> 00:38:35.470
It's the Anthropocene, where
humans and man-made technology

00:38:35.470 --> 00:38:38.650
determine the form,
the happenings,

00:38:38.650 --> 00:38:41.320
and the evolution on Earth.

00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:47.260
Every light spot represents a
big city and the light pattern

00:38:47.260 --> 00:38:51.130
as a whole for me
gives an idea about all

00:38:51.130 --> 00:38:57.400
issues of global urbanism,
about population explosion,

00:38:57.400 --> 00:39:03.190
about energy consumption, about
density, about neighborhoods

00:39:03.190 --> 00:39:06.730
if we are so close together
and if we have so many,

00:39:06.730 --> 00:39:13.180
about the demand
of land and food,

00:39:13.180 --> 00:39:15.190
about scale, about
[? heimat-- ?]

00:39:15.190 --> 00:39:19.620
it's typical German word
about responsibility,

00:39:19.620 --> 00:39:24.130
identity maybe, individuality.

00:39:24.130 --> 00:39:26.950
Now, while the
previous periods like

00:39:26.950 --> 00:39:30.460
starting with the
Pleistocene, which

00:39:30.460 --> 00:39:34.930
durated 2.8 million years
or 2.4 million years

00:39:34.930 --> 00:39:37.420
and then the Holocne
around 12,000 years,

00:39:37.420 --> 00:39:41.500
finally our Anthropocene at the
moment is like 200 years old.

00:39:41.500 --> 00:39:44.740
And it's called the time
of the big accelerations,

00:39:44.740 --> 00:39:49.570
looking on development of
population on this planet,

00:39:49.570 --> 00:39:52.360
material consumption, but
then as well the consequences

00:39:52.360 --> 00:39:57.520
in respect of losing nature,
in this case other people

00:39:57.520 --> 00:40:02.610
or created nature, but as well
kind of increasing pollution

00:40:02.610 --> 00:40:06.780
effects that we are created
by our technology applying

00:40:06.780 --> 00:40:10.970
to be able to live in
any spot on this planet.

00:40:10.970 --> 00:40:14.210
There are consequences
out of it, a side of it

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:18.770
that, for example, here
a picture of Beijing,

00:40:18.770 --> 00:40:22.340
the lower one represents
[? Beijing ?] of around 5%

00:40:22.340 --> 00:40:23.170
of the year.

00:40:23.170 --> 00:40:27.440
85% of the year, the
air quality in Beijing

00:40:27.440 --> 00:40:33.380
is described as unhealthy
or even hazardous.

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:36.800
And alone in China, they lose
like three million people

00:40:36.800 --> 00:40:39.300
a year just by air pollution.

00:40:39.300 --> 00:40:41.670
So [INAUDIBLE] it looks
like biotechnology

00:40:41.670 --> 00:40:46.020
and our kind of leftovers
from our technology

00:40:46.020 --> 00:40:49.190
we're kind of slowly
poisoning ourselves.

00:40:49.190 --> 00:40:51.310
As a side effect,
we know and Anya

00:40:51.310 --> 00:40:55.250
mentioned it, kind of
compared it to the Holocene

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:58.010
was 0.5 degrees
over 10,000 years,

00:40:58.010 --> 00:41:00.620
we are now in this
kind of 100 years

00:41:00.620 --> 00:41:03.020
increase already in
certain spots temperature

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:06.200
of this planet by 2.5 degrees.

00:41:06.200 --> 00:41:08.900
And then coming back to
the first presentation,

00:41:08.900 --> 00:41:13.210
in this case water will be our
big problem because suddenly,

00:41:13.210 --> 00:41:16.160
and I think we can't solve
it probably with an estuary,

00:41:16.160 --> 00:41:20.760
because [? interestingly ?]
now looking on this one,

00:41:20.760 --> 00:41:24.360
we are what we describe
nature now suddenly

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:25.770
will endanger culture.

00:41:25.770 --> 00:41:28.650
Because looking on all the
cultural cities along the East

00:41:28.650 --> 00:41:32.460
Coast of North America,
they will be all gone.

00:41:32.460 --> 00:41:36.090
So this in mind, but it's
not only endangering us,

00:41:36.090 --> 00:41:40.300
it's as well endangering any
life on this planet, nature.

00:41:40.300 --> 00:41:44.370
[? Like ?] nature, this
is kind of the birds,

00:41:44.370 --> 00:41:49.020
the [? found ?] birds reduction
just looking over the last 20

00:41:49.020 --> 00:41:54.000
years in this case in Germany,
looking back by the intensity

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:55.050
of our agriculture.

00:41:55.050 --> 00:41:57.330
Increasing the intensity
of our aquaculture,

00:41:57.330 --> 00:42:00.000
we are cutting down the
population of birds.

00:42:03.130 --> 00:42:05.970
And there have been
effects kind of looking

00:42:05.970 --> 00:42:10.290
on it that like in 2007, they
started to introduce kind

00:42:10.290 --> 00:42:17.850
of bio gas in Germany, which
increased kind of a lot of corn

00:42:17.850 --> 00:42:20.310
growing in Germany,
intensifying,

00:42:20.310 --> 00:42:24.300
creating big areas but kind of
cutting down the last refuges

00:42:24.300 --> 00:42:25.440
for nature.

00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:27.630
Now, what is interesting
on this one, which

00:42:27.630 --> 00:42:30.990
describes the kind of
status of the habitats

00:42:30.990 --> 00:42:34.140
of the different ecosystems,
just looking on three of them,

00:42:34.140 --> 00:42:36.900
the ocean and the
cropland and the urban.

00:42:36.900 --> 00:42:40.920
For the ocean, 85% of
the species in the ocean,

00:42:40.920 --> 00:42:45.740
we don't know what is
their status because we

00:42:45.740 --> 00:42:46.950
unknown their habits.

00:42:46.950 --> 00:42:50.070
What is interesting now looking
comparing cropland and urban,

00:42:50.070 --> 00:42:52.890
and I think this is now quite
interesting for our discussion

00:42:52.890 --> 00:42:56.640
on urban, that it looks
like nature in urban

00:42:56.640 --> 00:42:59.580
can find niches to
survive compared

00:42:59.580 --> 00:43:02.820
to intensive used
agricultural land

00:43:02.820 --> 00:43:06.420
because there is a large
diversity in cities

00:43:06.420 --> 00:43:09.540
and in natural
islands in the city.

00:43:09.540 --> 00:43:11.790
There are no fertilizers
and there's no hunting.

00:43:17.470 --> 00:43:23.280
These are [INAUDIBLE],
which I'm glad to say

00:43:23.280 --> 00:43:25.730
there are a lot of
them and some of them

00:43:25.730 --> 00:43:27.290
are really almost unbelievable.

00:43:27.290 --> 00:43:32.000
These wild pigs
which live in Rome,

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:34.910
I heard, and the biggest
nightingale population

00:43:34.910 --> 00:43:37.610
in Germany is in Berlin.

00:43:37.610 --> 00:43:43.040
The biggest hare population
lives in Stuttgart city center,

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:45.770
pumas in Los Angeles,
raccoons and foxes

00:43:45.770 --> 00:43:50.870
I think in almost every
city of the world meanwhile.

00:43:50.870 --> 00:43:53.210
What I found interesting
is that animals that

00:43:53.210 --> 00:43:58.610
used to be afraid of people,
they are coming so close.

00:43:58.610 --> 00:44:06.056
This is a kind of adaption
which is another example.

00:44:06.056 --> 00:44:10.760
These are the [? storks. ?]
Only a few decades ago,

00:44:10.760 --> 00:44:14.960
they left their territory if
somebody builds a small road

00:44:14.960 --> 00:44:16.340
and divides it into two pieces.

00:44:18.860 --> 00:44:21.710
In a very short time
later, nowadays storks

00:44:21.710 --> 00:44:24.290
have adapted to modern
living conditions.

00:44:24.290 --> 00:44:27.740
They have even changed
their migration routes

00:44:27.740 --> 00:44:30.140
and a lot of North
European storks

00:44:30.140 --> 00:44:35.960
don't fly to Africa anymore and
spend the winter on waste dumps

00:44:35.960 --> 00:44:38.890
in Spain eating leftovers.

00:44:43.590 --> 00:44:45.990
This is an example
from Stuttgart,

00:44:45.990 --> 00:44:51.820
where they found a population
of a protected species of lizard

00:44:51.820 --> 00:44:57.030
which settled down
and used holding

00:44:57.030 --> 00:44:59.730
tracks off the main station.

00:44:59.730 --> 00:45:03.930
And as the German railway
now wants to expand and build

00:45:03.930 --> 00:45:06.780
something on this
site, they really

00:45:06.780 --> 00:45:10.260
have a problem because following
the German law on nature

00:45:10.260 --> 00:45:12.330
[? conservation, ?]
they have to organize

00:45:12.330 --> 00:45:18.810
a complete resettlement
program for these lizards.

00:45:18.810 --> 00:45:21.440
Yeah.

00:45:21.440 --> 00:45:21.990
Oh, yeah.

