The complexity builds up.

01:15:46.504 --> 01:15:48.420
But I think that that
is the beauty, actually,

01:15:48.420 --> 01:15:51.680
of working with a particular
[? on the east coast. ?]

01:15:51.680 --> 01:15:54.010
While we can make a
kind of general comment,

01:15:54.010 --> 01:15:57.090
actually, on turning
the coast, it really

01:15:57.090 --> 01:16:02.930
requires very grassroots sort
of activity in terms of--

01:16:02.930 --> 01:16:05.040
and we've tried,
actually, to do that.

01:16:05.040 --> 01:16:07.890
But it really needs--

01:16:07.890 --> 01:16:10.230
that people are willing to
change governance, actually,

01:16:10.230 --> 01:16:13.090
so governance structures
in the Chesapeake.

01:16:13.090 --> 01:16:14.956
And that is happening slowly.

01:16:14.956 --> 01:16:16.830
so we are still in
conversation with the Army

01:16:16.830 --> 01:16:20.850
Corps of Engineers, actually,
working in that area.

01:16:20.850 --> 01:16:24.270
And we're dying to
actually do a pilot project

01:16:24.270 --> 01:16:27.870
where we can actually review
the diversity of these things.

01:16:27.870 --> 01:16:30.750
I'm not quite sure if I'm
answering your question, am I?

01:16:30.750 --> 01:16:32.880
- I just think would
be awfully interesting

01:16:32.880 --> 01:16:37.140
if all these towns
in jeopardy would

01:16:37.140 --> 01:16:40.320
have maps around the town
showing the high ground, low

01:16:40.320 --> 01:16:42.080
ground.

01:16:42.080 --> 01:16:44.210
Unless people know
what to-- this

01:16:44.210 --> 01:16:47.480
is a different way of thinking,
although in New Orleans

01:16:47.480 --> 01:16:49.850
they figured out pretty fast
where the high ground was,

01:16:49.850 --> 01:16:52.280
which were the overpasses.

01:16:52.280 --> 01:16:57.350
But it would just be
interesting to remap one's world

01:16:57.350 --> 01:16:58.670
into high ground, low ground.

01:16:58.670 --> 01:17:02.780
And it doesn't
rely on technology,

01:17:02.780 --> 01:17:12.387
it relies on nature helping
us, which is grade, elevation.

01:17:12.387 --> 01:17:13.720
- Can I take a little more time?

01:17:13.720 --> 01:17:18.092
I hope-- I don't want to be
taking time from the others.

01:17:18.092 --> 01:17:19.300
I just want to raise a point.

01:17:19.300 --> 01:17:21.640
I mean, one of the beautiful
things about thinking

01:17:21.640 --> 01:17:25.780
about high ground, low
ground versus a coastline

01:17:25.780 --> 01:17:29.290
is that when we read the
surface of the earth,

01:17:29.290 --> 01:17:32.210
actually, in terms of urban
and rural, for example,

01:17:32.210 --> 01:17:34.540
we are seeing
actually cities, which

01:17:34.540 --> 01:17:37.030
is a question, actually,
for the symposium,

01:17:37.030 --> 01:17:39.292
actually, which I sort of
find a little problematic.

01:17:39.292 --> 01:17:40.750
Because when we
use the term urban,

01:17:40.750 --> 01:17:43.930
we are actually using it
exclusively and excluding

01:17:43.930 --> 01:17:47.500
things that are outside of it.

01:17:47.500 --> 01:17:49.950
So when one refers to the
desert, et cetera, et cetera,

01:17:49.950 --> 01:17:51.574
one is actually
positioning it outside.

01:17:51.574 --> 01:17:55.180
And I wonder sometimes what
one is positioning outside

01:17:55.180 --> 01:17:55.726
of the city.

01:17:55.726 --> 01:17:57.100
But that reading,
actually, where

01:17:57.100 --> 01:17:59.710
the city has been given
a measure to things

01:17:59.710 --> 01:18:02.080
is very different from a
middle ground, for example.

01:18:02.080 --> 01:18:04.390
And so if I actually
do maps that

01:18:04.390 --> 01:18:06.940
work with drawing
the middle ground out

01:18:06.940 --> 01:18:09.112
as the agency with
which we work,

01:18:09.112 --> 01:18:11.320
you get a completely different
structuring, actually,

01:18:11.320 --> 01:18:13.780
of the surface of the
Earth, as compared

01:18:13.780 --> 01:18:17.620
to working with cities
that you can then

01:18:17.620 --> 01:18:22.297
talk about as successes, which
is to me extremely problematic.

01:18:22.297 --> 01:18:24.130
But I don't want to get
into that discussion

01:18:24.130 --> 01:18:26.671
because it all depends on how
you define the problem in order

01:18:26.671 --> 01:18:30.030
to fit the solution.

01:18:30.030 --> 01:18:32.910
- The solution-- I think one
of the problems here is that

01:18:32.910 --> 01:18:35.640
if you look at the projections--
there are maps, by the way,

01:18:35.640 --> 01:18:38.550
available showing what sea
level rise would do to coastal

01:18:38.550 --> 01:18:41.250
cities, but yet money is
pouring into [? Seaport ?]

01:18:41.250 --> 01:18:45.060
or into Miami Beach on
the premise, I suspect,

01:18:45.060 --> 01:18:49.470
that by the time disaster
hits in 2050 or 2070,

01:18:49.470 --> 01:18:52.240
we'll have our money, the
original owners have sold it,

01:18:52.240 --> 01:18:54.060
if they even can sell it.

01:18:54.060 --> 01:18:56.114
But looking up the
heat issue, if you

01:18:56.114 --> 01:18:58.155
look at the projections
for the Arabian Peninsula

01:18:58.155 --> 01:19:02.130
with [? wet ?] bulb
temperatures, by 2050 or 2060,

01:19:02.130 --> 01:19:04.080
there won't be very
cool winds coming off

01:19:04.080 --> 01:19:06.000
in the humidity ranges needed.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:08.680
So trying to design
in today's parameters

01:19:08.680 --> 01:19:12.750
but ignoring 25 or 30 years
out, let alone 50 or 100.

01:19:12.750 --> 01:19:16.620
At one time you could
walk from Boston Light

01:19:16.620 --> 01:19:20.790
during the glacial maximum all
the way out to the George's

01:19:20.790 --> 01:19:22.560
Bank.

01:19:22.560 --> 01:19:25.410
70 meters is a lot to
overcome and you're not

01:19:25.410 --> 01:19:29.744
going to do it by trying to
imitate Dutch technology.

01:19:29.744 --> 01:19:32.160
It will buy a few years, but
that's all it's going to buy.

01:19:32.160 --> 01:19:33.618
So I guess my
question of the panel

01:19:33.618 --> 01:19:35.400
is, when are we going
to start looking

01:19:35.400 --> 01:19:40.050
at reasonable projections,
rather than sort of work

01:19:40.050 --> 01:19:43.890
on these very narrow
timeframes of 20 or 30 years

01:19:43.890 --> 01:19:45.470
and ignore the fact
that it's going

01:19:45.470 --> 01:19:47.490
to be a lot different
by the time I'm dead

01:19:47.490 --> 01:19:48.937
and everybody in
this room is dead

01:19:48.937 --> 01:19:50.520
but our children and
our grandchildren

01:19:50.520 --> 01:19:52.270
will have to face a
whole different world?

01:19:56.340 --> 01:19:58.980
- I would see we are
looking on the next years

01:19:58.980 --> 01:20:02.460
because politically, the
decisions we do the next years,

01:20:02.460 --> 01:20:05.220
they will determine the next
50 and the next 100 years.

01:20:05.220 --> 01:20:08.970
Because the time is so
late that our decisions are

01:20:08.970 --> 01:20:13.170
so critical that expecting that
this might be solved though

01:20:13.170 --> 01:20:16.970
the technology in 10 or
15 years, that's too late.

01:20:16.970 --> 01:20:20.660
And I think this is the
dangerous kind of performance

01:20:20.660 --> 01:20:24.570
or habit of climate change,
that you don't feel it

01:20:24.570 --> 01:20:26.670
before it really
strikes and then it's

01:20:26.670 --> 01:20:30.080
too late because the
system is so big.

01:20:30.080 --> 01:20:31.480
And this is nature.

01:20:31.480 --> 01:20:34.830
So this has been, again
back to the discussion

01:20:34.830 --> 01:20:37.530
that in a certain way,
we messed that up.

01:20:37.530 --> 01:20:40.470
And the question is, are
we able to bring it back

01:20:40.470 --> 01:20:41.710
to a certain performance?

01:20:41.710 --> 01:20:45.040
I think the planet will
survive because it survived

01:20:45.040 --> 01:20:47.130
other waves of temperature.

01:20:47.130 --> 01:20:51.218
The question is if the
human period will survive.

01:20:53.610 --> 01:20:54.110
- All right.

01:20:54.110 --> 01:20:58.660
I think we can wrap
it up with that.

01:20:58.660 --> 01:20:59.560
No.

01:20:59.560 --> 01:21:00.460
Please.

01:21:00.460 --> 01:21:03.210
[APPLAUSE]

